title: Carbon nano coating US
author: Maxsym
description:
**Summary**
Carbon nanotubes (CNTs) are some of the most promising materials to result from nanotechnology, and are used globally in a wide range of products in energy, electronics, textiles, optics etc.  However there is a potential for inhalation by workers through processing CNT, and evidence that types of CNTs have fibre characteristics not unlike asbestos which have been associated with elevated risk of lung cancer and mesothelioma in humans and animals.  The risk of inhalation decreases as the product is processed and incorporated into other products.  This risk can also be substantially reduced by taking appropriate precautions.  There is no current evidence that the public using those products has any exposure, or that there is exposure other than by inhalation although there is the possibility of environmental impact from factory waste with CNTs.  The estimated future size of [employee liability related] loss for the US is anticipated to be in the range of $111M to $8.5B.

**Size of the event**: In the US the losses due to workers compensation [and other environmental losses] that may occur range from $111M to $8.5B for accidents and exposures occurring between year 2000 to 2030 and claims made between 2025 to 2055.

**Lines of business impacted**: Workers compensation is the primary line of business impacted, but it could potentially impact general liability, environmental liability and D&O.

**Status of the event:**  There appear to have been no losses to date.

**Spread of event:**  This is a potentially global event.  There are [6432] [131] products being made using carbon nanotubes.  USA and China are the largest producers of carbon nanotubes in the world, having 34% and 32% respectively, Turkey the next largest with 12% of the production of carbon nanotube products, followed by India, Germany, Belgium, Australia, and Taiwan. Belarus, Canada, South Korea, Cyprus, France, Hong Kong, Iran, Singapore, Finland, Austria, Japan, Greece, Israel, Turkey, Switzerland, Czech Republic, Norway, Russia, Slovenia, and the United Kingdom are also manufacturing carbon nanotubes or products. The estimated workforce handling CNT in the US in the year 2009 was approximately 650 people. 
Who is held primarily responsible for the harm: If workers suffer injury, it is very likely that the manufacturers employing or contracting for the workers will be held primarily responsible.

**Who may also be held responsible for the harm:**  Manufacturers and distributors of the carbon nanotubes or derived material may also be held liable for the harm if they didn’t provide adequate warnings and advice on handling the material, as well as those who advised on safety procedures, or safety equipment that appears faulty or not fit for the purpose for which it was used.  If there is shown to be a risk to patients from medical implants, than the physicians and hospitals may also be liable, and if there is an environmental impact, those advising on and responsible for dealing with the waste could have some liability.

**Nature of harm:**  Primarily death and bodily injury including pain and suffering and chronic illness. 

**What mechanism causes the harm:** Inhalation of the carbon nanotubes has been linked to lung cancer, COPD and idiophatic fibrosis. There is a limit concentration of CNT in the atmosphere of the working place (1 µg/m3) below which the risk of being injured increases by 10% to the risk of the wider population. Research has proven that CNT cause changes at the molecular level in the body but the scope of the possible damages from this and other diseases could be triggered from CNT is currently unknown. 

CNT can potentially also be harmful for the environment, damaging plants or the soil or fish in case they are released into a water stream, or potentially damaging patients if the CNT in implants leaches into the body and causes harm.  

**Who or what is harmed**: Workers handling or in the vicinity to inhale carbon nanotubes in the factory [any possible environmental damage] during production, packaging, shipping, or disposal of waste. 

The environment could be harmed if there is an accident in the factories or during shipping that releases CNT and those go to the atmosphere or into water streams or in the case that the final product changes its form and releases CNT back into the atmosphere. 

**Circumstances of harm**: It appears that there needs to be a concentration of CNT in the atmosphere of the working place (1 µg/m3) for damage to occur.

**Period of time over which the harm could occur:** CNT industry is new industry and the projected growth rate until 2024 is 15% to 22% per year. Injuries are expected to appear towards the end of the working life of the employees i.e. for workers who were in the manufacturing factories from year 2000 will develop injuries by year 2025.
